x4freetext: Handbook on nuclear
activation data
Three samples (112Sn, natSn and Cu) were placed
in that order in a stick-like arrangement along the
deuteron beam axis and were irradiated by the same
incident neutron flux. These disks (triad) were weighed
and grouped into three stacks.
Three enriched samples and two natural sample were used
in the set of experiments.
Two 112Sn targets enriched to 62.5% with masses
72.5 mg and 911.1 mg were cut to disks of diam. 7 mm
and 10.9 mm and thicknesses 0.3 mm and 0.16 mm,
respectively. The third enriched sample with 84%
enrichment was also shaped to disk of 5.1 mm diam.,
0.15 mm thickness and of mass 20.6 mg. The 5.6 g sample
of natural tin (diameter 22 mm, thickness 2.2 mm) was
prepared from spectrographically pure tin. The second
1.88 g sample of natural tin foil 44 mm in diam. and
0.17 mm thick had purity better than 99%.
Abundance in the natural sample is: 112Sn - 0.971%;
Abundance in the inriched sample 1. is:
Abundance in the inriched sample 2. is: 112Sn-84.0%;
Small, enriched irradiated samples of 112Sn
were measured on a 72 cm3 Ge(Li) spectrometer.
The natural tin samples and Cu monitors with higher
masses and dimensions were measured using another
spectrometer with large 177 cm3 Ge(Li) detector
Two different types of neutron detectors have been
used: 1. a multi sphere Bonner type neutron detector;
2. a second detector in the form of copper disks. The
copper monitor foil 44 mm diam. 1 mm thick
(mass 13.25 g) was 99.9% pure.
The decay-data were from database NuDaT 2.0, 2004
http://www-nds.iaea.org/nudat2
Total error. Uncertainties in the cross
section values reported in this work are composed of
uncertainties from various sources entering into well
known activation formula. The dominant sources are:
* gamma-ray detector efficiency (5%),
* photo-peak counting statistics (1 to 18%),
* neutron flux determination (standard cross section
of the 65Cu(n,2n)64Cu for the neutron flux monitor
with error +-3%),
* error of the half-lives (1 to 18%),
* the gamma-ray branching ratios (1 to 14%),
* cascade (coincidence) summing (1 to 33%) for
close geometry (source-to-detector distance
0.3 cm) and
* self-absorption of gamma-rays in the sample (1%).
Other uncertaities, such as sample weight, isotopic
abundance, irradiation, cooling and measuring time
were of the order of 0.1 % each.
Wherever it was possible, the authors used a few gamma
lines for the activity (cross section) determination.
In such a case the final value was calculated by
weighting the values of cross sections with their
errors. Of course the result was dominated by the value
of the cross section with the smallest uncertainty.
